  "prompt": "Are there legal distinctions between different types of money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are legal distinctions between different types of money laundering, and these distinctions can vary depending on the jurisdiction. Here are some common categories and distinctions:\n\n1. **Traditional Money Laundering**:\n   - **Definition**: The process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\").\n   - **Methods**: This typically involves three stages: placement (introducing the illicit funds into the financial system), layering (concealing the source of the funds through a series of transactions), and integration (reintroducing the funds into the economy as legitimate assets).\n\n2. **Structuring (Smurfing)**:\n   - **Definition**: Breaking down large amounts of money into smaller, less suspicious amounts to avoid detection by financial institutions and regulatory authorities.\n   - **Legal Distinction**: Often treated as a separate offense due to its specific method of evading reporting requirements.\n\n3",
